WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:08.000
Hey y'all, and welcome to the 7th Enterprise Community Meetup, where we talk about end-to-end data science workflows with Posit Team.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:15.000
My name is Simon Couch, and I work on free and open source packages for machine learning in R at Posit.

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:21.000
In today's session, I'm going to walk through an example of training and deploying a machine learning model.

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:29.000
I'll be leaning heavily on the tidymodels, which is a framework for machine learning in R that I work on, to develop my model.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:36.000
Along the way, I'll show you how Posit Team eases some of the pain points of model development that I encounter.

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:41.000
During today's session, I'll lay out three high-level steps for building a machine learning model,

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:50.000
and then spend some time with each of those steps individually before concluding with resources where you can learn more about tidymodels and about Posit Team.

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:58.000
After I present, we'll be hanging out for a live Q&A, so please feel free to ask questions as we go, and I'm looking forward to spending time.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:01.000
But with all that out of the way, let's go ahead and get started.

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:06.000
To talk about those first and second steps, I'll make use of some slides.

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:13.000
And then for step three, I'll drop into a live demo using Posit Connect and Posit Workbench.

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:20.000
If you're interested in spending more time with these slides or checking out the source code behind this presentation,

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:29.000
you can go to the link in the footer of these slides. That's github.com slash simonpcouch slash mutagen.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:36.000
I've put together a diagram of sort of the high-level process for developing a machine learning model.

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:44.000
And the three steps that I'm talking about are kind of called out with these three hex stickers in the corners.

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:51.000
In the top right corner, that first step is to collect data and to spend time with it.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:59.000
Cleaning data, visualizing it, understanding it are all important first steps to building a machine learning model.

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:06.000
When I do each of those steps, I end up spending a lot of time with the Tidyverse packages, which some of you may have heard of.

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:14.000
Once I move on to training and evaluating models, I use the Tidymodels packages, which I work on day-to-day.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:26.000
And a common issue that people run into when they're building models with Tidymodels or any model development software is running out of computational resources.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:33.000
If you're working in an environment with lots of data or you're trying to evaluate really complex models,

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:36.000
you can run out of computational resources really quickly.

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:42.000
And for me, this is a place where Posit Workbench is really key.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:46.000
Recently, I've started using it when I run into this situation.

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:57.000
And it allows me to drop into a computational environment where I have more resources and can complete that model training more quickly.

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:02.000
Once a model is trained, it's time to get it into the hands of people that will use it.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:05.000
And that's where the Vetiver package comes in.

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:20.000
Vetiver is free and open source, and it provides tools to version models, deploy models, and monitor them to ensure that they continue to perform as you expect them to once they're out into the world.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:24.000
Vetiver is tightly integrated with Posit Connect.

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:31.000
Which offers all sorts of tooling for getting the outputs of analysis into the right hands.

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:39.000
So first, let's talk about what do I even mean when I say machine learning or a machine learning model.

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:44.000
One example is a Netflix movie recommendation.

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:52.000
If you've ever gone to somebody else's house and seen the movies that are recommended to them, you might know that they're a Netflix movie.

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:58.000
And if you look at the movies that are recommended to them, you might notice that they're quite different than what you might see at your own house.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:06.000
That's because the movies that are recommended to you and the thumbnails that are part of those recommendations are outputs of machine learning models.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:15.000
And based on your viewing history and the things that you've said you're interested in, Netflix will recommend different movies to you.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:29.000
Another example, on Zillow, if you're looking at houses or apartments, there are estimates of the value of the property or the rent that they would expect you to pay if you were to live there.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:32.000
So that's another example of a machine learning model.

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:35.000
Or email spam filters.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:49.000
So all of our emails, whenever we get an email, at first there's a filter that looks at the subject line and if you've received an email from that person before and if there are any typos inside of the email.

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:56.000
And based on information like that, a model will try to predict whether an email is spam or not.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:00.000
And if it does predict that the email is spam, it will go to a folder.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:10.000
So the thing that all of these share is that they are guessing the value of an outcome using predictors.

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:16.000
For example, in the email spam filters, the outcome is whether that email is spam or not.

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:24.000
And the predictors are those things I mentioned, like the subject line and the number of typos inside and other things like that.

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:36.000
For a Zillow property value estimate, that might be something like the square footage of the house or the apartment, how recently it was renovated, what area it's in.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:47.000
And for Netflix movie recommendations, that's things like your stated interest in movies that you're interested in to how long you spent watching movies in different subcategories.

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:53.000
Another example of a machine learning model is one that this presentation is based on.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:58.000
Day to day, my responsibility is just to develop tools to build models.

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:06.000
And so I often don't spend a lot of time building models myself, but doing so helps us better understand the perspectives of our users.

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:12.000
And so we try to make time to really delve in on a modeling problem as often as we can.

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:26.000
So recently, my colleague Max Kuhn and I spent some time to develop a model and work through the process to deploy it using Posit Workbench and Posit Connect and wrote about that on the Posit blog.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:40.000
In this blog post, we talked through a process that's really similar to the one that I'll talk through with you today, where we explore data, we situate with our modeling problem.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:46.000
We develop a model to best understand that data, and then we deploy it using Connect.

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:57.000
So the process of machine learning with Posit Team, again, I'll just underscore those three different sections before we dive in on them.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:02.000
First, we'll spend some time to understand and clean data with the Tidyverse.

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:07.000
And then we'll train and evaluate models with Tidy Models and Workbench.

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:10.000
For both of these sections, I'll just work through some slides.

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:23.000
And if you're interested in the details, you can look at the source code of the analysis and the source code for these slides at github.com slash chimeinpeakcouch slash mutagen.

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:29.000
Once we've done so, we need to get that model into the hands of users.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:32.000
And that's where Vetiver and Connect come in.

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:37.000
So let's start off with understanding and cleaning data.

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:48.000
In pharmaceuticals, mutagenicity refers to a drug's tendency to increase the rate of mutations due to damage caused to DNA.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:56.000
Mutagenicity is a key indicator that a drug may be a carcinogen or a cancer-causing.

00:07:57.000 --> 00:08:00.000
Mutagenicity can be evaluated with a lab test.

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:07.000
So a person can test whether a drug is a mutagen using a standard wet lab procedure.

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:11.000
But those tests are costly, and those tests are time-intensive.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:18.000
So a group of scientists in our example problem converges to ask the question,

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:23.000
What if a machine learning model could predict mutagenicity using known drug information?

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:30.000
That is, if scientists are spending time with a new drug, using information that they already have,

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:38.000
they can predict whether a drug is a mutagen or not, which will allow them to iterate more quickly when they're developing new drugs.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:45.000
The source data that we'll be working with is called mutagen table data.

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:51.000
It's a table with over 4,000 rows and notably over 1,500 predictors.

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:58.000
So in this first column, we have whether the drug is a mutagen or whether it's a non-mutagen.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:10.000
And for each of those compounds as well, we have a whole lot of predictors giving us other information we can use to predict whether a drug is a mutagen or not.

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:16.000
So you're probably thinking to yourself, if I have 1,500 little pieces of information about this drug,

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:20.000
it surely must be pretty straightforward to predict that.

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:24.000
It turns out it's not quite that simple.

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:36.000
On this plot, I've plotted two of the predictors, and each of those points is also colored according to whether the drug is actually a mutagen or not.

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:42.000
The points is also colored according to whether the drug is actually a mutagen or whether it's a non-mutagen.

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:47.000
So colors in blue are mutagens, colors in yellow are non-mutagens.

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:53.000
On the x-axis, we have the molecular weight, and y-axis is the partition coefficient.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:57.000
It doesn't matter whether you understand either of these two predictors.

00:09:58.000 --> 00:09:59.000
I really don't understand them.

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:12.000
But the point here is that it's really hard just using the information we have here to separate between the blue points and the yellow points, only knowing the value of these two predictors.

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:16.000
I can choose another two of them.

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:23.000
Right now I'm showing the number of heavy atoms and the log of the average valence connectivity.

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:35.000
Whatever those two predictors mean, again we're seeing that it's really hard to draw a line here that would easily separate the blue points and the yellow points.

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:39.000
And this is the goal that our machine learning model will try to solve.

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:45.000
So if you're like me, you're feeling a little bit intimidated about tackling this.

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:50.000
This is where we move on to the step of training and evaluating models.

00:10:51.000 --> 00:11:07.000
So for this portion of the presentation, instead of walking through the notebook that does the training and the evaluating, I'll leave it to folks to look through the notebooks that are on that GitHub page after the presentation.

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:17.000
And instead, I'll try to answer the question of why you might be interested in using tidy models over other modeling frameworks that are out there.

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:31.000
The first reason why you should be interested in using tidy models is that tidy models is consistent in a way that other modeling frameworks and modeling packages are not.

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:49.000
An example that I'll use to call this out here, we can start off by showing the code to fit a linear model using the lm function with tidy models and a linear model using only the lm function.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:57.000
On the left hand side, there's just one line of code. We're using the example mtcars dataset here if you're familiar with it.

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:10.000
We're saying we want to use all of the predictors in the mtcars data to predict the outcome, which is the miles per gallon or mpg.

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:14.000
And to do so, we'll use the mtcars data.

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:23.000
On the right hand side, the code does the same thing, except the tidy models wrapper has been dropped on top of that function.

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:42.000
The code reads, we'll use a linear regression using the lm function as our computational engine and we'll fit that model using the same dataset and the same preprocessing formula, mpg, as a function of everything.

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:53.000
When you see this, you might think it seems a whole lot easier to just go ahead and use lm, it's only one line of code, and I hear you.

00:12:54.000 --> 00:13:01.000
Where we really see the value of tidy models, though, is when we start to introduce complexity into the modeling pipeline.

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:12.000
So let's say you're using the lm function and it's not doing everything you need it to do, and you want to add, for example, a regularization term to your linear regression.

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:18.000
If you're not familiar with that, it doesn't matter to understand what I'm about to demonstrate here.

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:26.000
I want you to look at that line 3 in the tidy models portion of the code where I've set the engine to lm.

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:38.000
If I want to transition that code to instead use glmnet, all that I need to do is change the portion of the code that said lm to instead say glmnet.

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:47.000
And you can see on the left hand side, it was much more than just one of the lines of code that needed to change.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:55.000
Instead, here, glmnet, for its first argument, is going to take all of the predictors and they can only be a matrix.

00:13:56.000 --> 00:14:07.000
So thankfully, here, in empty cars, all of the predictors are numbers anyway, and so they're one homogenous type and we can easily convert it with as.matrix.

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:21.000
And then instead of the name of the outcome variable like it was in lm, the outcome here is specified as the actual vector of values in the empty cars dataset.

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:25.000
So that's empty cars dollar sign mpg.

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:34.000
To transition that code, I needed to know not only that glmnet existed and was able to perform regularization,

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:41.000
but I needed to look at the documentation to see how that function wanted the predictors to be formatted,

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:47.000
how it wanted the outcome to be formatted, whether it needed any additional arguments,

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:51.000
which of the functions in the package I needed to use to do so.

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:58.000
And again, in tidy models, all I needed to do was change the value of that engine argument.

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:03.000
And the story goes the same way with any other engine you can imagine.

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:16.000
Let's say instead of glmnet, I wanted to use the h2o package, which gives me access to all sorts of machine learning techniques implemented in Java so it's super fast.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:21.000
With tidy models, all I need to do is change the value of engine to h2o.

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:25.000
But with h2o, I need to initialize an h2o server.

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:34.000
I need to convert that empty cars dataset to a dataset that's compatible with h2o using as.h2o.

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:40.000
And I assign a label to that empty cars dataset, the string empty cars.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:46.000
And then I pass that string as the last argument to h2o's linear model.

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:54.000
And then I pass that string as the last argument to h2o's linear model function, h2o.glm.

00:15:56.000 --> 00:16:03.000
Also, the h2o.glm function doesn't take the values of the predictors, instead it takes the names.

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:10.000
So I take the names of the empty cars dataset, the portion of it that has the predictors in it.

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:17.000
And the same goes for the outcome. It takes the name of the outcome in the empty cars dataset as a string.

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:29.000
So all of this change in the code, again, I would need to spend time to read through the documentation, see how that interface changes.

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:35.000
And only once I've done so can I make use of the functionality within h2o.

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:40.000
And with TidyModels, I just get that for free by changing the engine argument.

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:47.000
Another reason to use TidyModels is safety.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:53.000
TidyModels is designed to safeguard you from common modeling pitfalls.

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:59.000
One of the things that TidyModels is designed to protect you from is data leakage.

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:05.000
A 2023 review found data leakage to be a widespread failure mode in machine learning-based science.

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:21.000
Data leakage is when information from the set you're going to use, or the portion of the data that you're going to use to evaluate your model, somehow leaks into the portion of the data that you're using to train your model.

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:32.000
If a model is being evaluated on data that it's seen already, then it will perform better than on data that it hasn't seen before.

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:42.000
And so it will seem like your model is performing really well, but it's actually not, and you'll only learn that the model isn't performing well once it's deployed.

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:55.000
So in our example, in the mutagen example, if our model seems to be able to classify drugs as either mutagens or non-mutagens really, really well,

00:17:56.000 --> 00:18:01.000
if we go ahead and deploy that, thinking that the model is performing perfectly,

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:11.000
then scientists will mistakenly interpret the results from that model and take them at face value.

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:17.000
Another common failure mode is overfitting.

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:23.000
Overfitting leads to analysts believing models are more performant than they actually are.

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:31.000
So this is really similar to that first failure mode, where in the case of an overfit model, in our mutagen example,

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:40.000
the model is going to perform really, really well on the portion of the data that was used to train the model.

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:46.000
And if we don't have tools to then evaluate the model on data that it hasn't seen before,

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:56.000
then that model might just learn every little intricacy of the training data and won't generalize well to data that it hasn't seen before.

00:18:57.000 --> 00:19:06.000
A last component of safety that tidy models make sure to protect its users from is irreproducibility.

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:17.000
Implementations of the same machine learning model give differing results in many popular implementations of machine learning algorithms,

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:21.000
resulting in irreproducibility of modeling results.

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:31.000
So each of the citations listed in the bottom here in order are reports on data leakage and overfitting and irreproducibility.

00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:35.000
And tidy models is designed to safeguard you from all of them.

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:44.000
We developed this software so that it's really hard to do the things that are wrong and that an analyst would commonly want to do,

00:19:45.000 --> 00:19:52.000
and makes the things that are usually difficult but pay off in the long run, it makes those things really easy.

00:19:56.000 --> 00:20:02.000
Another reason why you might want to use tidy models is that tidy models is designed to be communicable.

00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:11.000
All tidy models objects, or at least many of them, have visualization functions called autoplot that are associated with them.

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:21.000
So if I make a receiver operating curve with the tidy models, which is a tool used to evaluate models,

00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:28.000
I can pass that object to autoplot and see what that curve looks like in 2D space.

00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:33.000
I can also pass, for example, the results of trying to tune a random forest algorithm.

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:42.000
Again, I just pass that result to the autoplot function, and we have built-in visualization procedures for that model object.

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:47.000
The same story goes for iterative search results.

00:20:48.000 --> 00:20:51.000
Things like Bayesian optimization, simulated annealing,

00:20:52.000 --> 00:20:57.000
these are advanced machine learning techniques that are built into tidy models.

00:20:58.000 --> 00:21:03.000
When I use tidy models to generate these results, I can understand them by quickly plotting them.

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:09.000
Another example to use tidy models is completeness.

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:16.000
There's built-in support for 99 machine learning models once you load the tidy models packages,

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:24.000
and there are even more packages if you load extensions that are contributed by the community.

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:31.000
Tidy models is also complete with reference to data preprocessing techniques.

00:21:32.000 --> 00:21:36.000
With the three main packages for preprocessing that are loaded when you load tidy models,

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:42.000
we load in 102 different ways to process data that comes in raw,

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:46.000
and turn it into something that a model knows what to do with.

00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:53.000
I've hinted at this already, but again, tidy models is extensible.

00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:56.000
If you can't find the machine learning technique you need,

00:21:57.000 --> 00:22:01.000
which is either the machine learning model or the preprocessing technique,

00:22:02.000 --> 00:22:03.000
you can add it yourself.

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:09.000
We have APIs that are designed to make it really easy to contribute your own extensions

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:13.000
that are designed with your problem context in mind.

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:18.000
The last reason I'll list here is deployability,

00:22:19.000 --> 00:22:24.000
and this will bring us into that final step three that we'll drop into the live demo for.

00:22:25.000 --> 00:22:27.000
Tidy models is tightly integrated with Vetiver,

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:30.000
which is a free and open-source package for model deployment.

00:22:31.000 --> 00:22:38.000
And Vetiver is configured to quickly and easily and securely ship a model to Posit Connect,

00:22:39.000 --> 00:22:42.000
which is part of the suite of products in Posit Team.

