00:24:13.000 --> 00:24:18.000
I'm going to go ahead and copy the link to this GitHub repository,

00:24:18.000 --> 00:24:21.000
and then I will start a new project,

00:24:22.000 --> 00:24:26.000
and the new project will be from version control.

00:24:27.000 --> 00:24:31.000
I'll start it up from Git, and paste in the URL there,

00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:34.000
and I'll call this project mutagen.

00:24:35.000 --> 00:24:39.000
This will also just take a couple seconds to spin up,

00:24:40.000 --> 00:24:44.000
and once it's done so, all of the data and the source files

00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:47.000
that were inside of that GitHub repository

00:24:48.000 --> 00:24:53.000
are going to be also available to me inside of Posit Workbench.

00:24:55.000 --> 00:24:58.000
So for instance, there's a readme in this repository

00:24:59.000 --> 00:25:02.000
giving some high-level information on what's in there.

00:25:03.000 --> 00:25:06.000
Here's all the source code for the slides in this slide folder.

00:25:07.000 --> 00:25:09.000
What I'm going to open up is a source here,

00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:13.000
which has a Cordo document that has all of the source code

00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:19.000
that I used to pre-process my data and start understanding it in step one,

00:25:20.000 --> 00:25:22.000
and then moving into that step two,

00:25:23.000 --> 00:25:26.000
which is developing and training the model,

00:25:27.000 --> 00:25:29.000
and ultimately deciding on the final fit.

00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:32.000
So you can see up here in my environment,

00:25:33.000 --> 00:25:38.000
I went ahead and loaded in the output of final fit from file.

00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:42.000
So normally in my workflow, I would go ahead and train the model

00:25:42.000 --> 00:25:45.000
here on Workbench, and since I've done so already,

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:48.000
I already have the output of that from here,

00:25:49.000 --> 00:25:52.000
and instead we're going to move right on to that last step, step three,

00:25:53.000 --> 00:25:55.000
which is getting that trained model into the hands

00:25:56.000 --> 00:25:58.000
of the people that are going to use it.

00:25:59.000 --> 00:26:00.000
This is actually really simple.

00:26:01.000 --> 00:26:03.000
There's only a few lines of code you need

00:26:04.000 --> 00:26:06.000
once you have a fitted model with tidy models

00:26:07.000 --> 00:26:10.000
to then go ahead and deploy that model to Posit Connect.

00:26:11.000 --> 00:26:15.000
The first step is to pass that trained model to vetever model,

00:26:16.000 --> 00:26:18.000
which is a function from vetever,

00:26:19.000 --> 00:26:20.000
which will put some wrappers around it

00:26:21.000 --> 00:26:23.000
and make sure it's ready to go to deploy.

00:26:24.000 --> 00:26:28.000
I'll also call board connect here and assign that output to board.

00:26:29.000 --> 00:26:32.000
If you're unfamiliar with this function, this is from pins,

00:26:33.000 --> 00:26:36.000
and if you want to learn more about the pins package,

00:26:36.000 --> 00:26:39.000
I think it was the last Posit Team demo

00:26:40.000 --> 00:26:42.000
where they covered the functionality there.

00:26:43.000 --> 00:26:46.000
We're running into an error here, and what this is telling me

00:26:47.000 --> 00:26:49.000
is that we don't have a Posit Connect server

00:26:50.000 --> 00:26:52.000
that we're connected to already,

00:26:53.000 --> 00:26:55.000
so we can actually go ahead and do that, and it's pretty simple.

00:26:56.000 --> 00:27:00.000
If I go to Tools, Global Options, Publishing,

00:27:01.000 --> 00:27:04.000
these are the accounts from which I can publish from.

00:27:04.000 --> 00:27:08.000
I'm going to go ahead and just click Connect here to Posit Connect,

00:27:09.000 --> 00:27:11.000
and this is pre-filled for me

00:27:12.000 --> 00:27:14.000
because I'm working on my Workbench instance

00:27:15.000 --> 00:27:18.000
inside of a Posit Team account.

00:27:19.000 --> 00:27:22.000
That's pre-filled in there. I'll click Next.

00:27:23.000 --> 00:27:25.000
It's going to wait for authentication,

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:29.000
and it will authenticate to my Posit account,

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:32.000
and now that it's authenticated,

00:27:32.000 --> 00:27:36.000
I can click Connect Account and Apply,

00:27:37.000 --> 00:27:39.000
and so that's all I needed to do

00:27:40.000 --> 00:27:44.000
to link my Workbench session up to Posit Connect.

00:27:45.000 --> 00:27:48.000
So I can try running that board Connect code again,

00:27:49.000 --> 00:27:52.000
and it was successful. Nice.

00:27:53.000 --> 00:27:57.000
So I'm on the Connect instance that I have access to through Posit.

00:27:58.000 --> 00:28:00.000
I will then pass that final fit object,

00:28:00.000 --> 00:28:02.000
the vetiver made to me.

00:28:03.000 --> 00:28:06.000
It's a vetiver pin write to write it to the board I've just created,

00:28:07.000 --> 00:28:11.000
and now that final fit vetiver object

00:28:12.000 --> 00:28:14.000
is pinned to the board on Posit Connect.

00:28:15.000 --> 00:28:18.000
So once that pin is on Connect,

00:28:19.000 --> 00:28:21.000
I'll go ahead and deploy the model

00:28:22.000 --> 00:28:26.000
that I have assigned to this Simon Couch slash Mutagen,

00:28:27.000 --> 00:28:29.000
and you'll see here down in the console

00:28:30.000 --> 00:28:32.000
that vetiver is doing all sorts of work

00:28:33.000 --> 00:28:35.000
to bundle up everything that that model needs

00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:38.000
to create predictions from new data

00:28:39.000 --> 00:28:44.000
into an object that can be passed off to Connect.

00:28:45.000 --> 00:28:47.000
So that happened pretty quickly.

00:28:48.000 --> 00:28:51.000
It just brought us over to a Connect window

00:28:52.000 --> 00:28:54.000
where vetiver is showing the deployment.

00:28:54.000 --> 00:28:57.000
So on the left side of the screen is what a user would see

00:28:58.000 --> 00:29:00.000
if they pulled up this model API,

00:29:01.000 --> 00:29:03.000
and so there's all sorts of metadata about the model.

00:29:04.000 --> 00:29:07.000
There's examples from which analysts can ping,

00:29:08.000 --> 00:29:12.000
put together code to ping the model for new predictions.

00:29:13.000 --> 00:29:15.000
And then on the right side,

00:29:16.000 --> 00:29:18.000
and this is a really nice benefit for a lot of people,

00:29:19.000 --> 00:29:22.000
there's all sorts of access to security features

00:29:22.000 --> 00:29:24.000
and metadata.

00:29:25.000 --> 00:29:28.000
So by default, it's only available to specific users or groups,

00:29:29.000 --> 00:29:31.000
and you can add those in,

00:29:32.000 --> 00:29:34.000
but you can also make it available to all users

00:29:35.000 --> 00:29:37.000
within your organization.

00:29:38.000 --> 00:29:40.000
And then there's all sorts of other metadata

00:29:41.000 --> 00:29:43.000
that you have access to as well.

00:29:44.000 --> 00:29:46.000
So I hadn't deployed a model using vetiver

00:29:47.000 --> 00:29:50.000
until I was working on the blog post that I mentioned earlier,

00:29:50.000 --> 00:29:54.000
and I was really surprised at how straightforwardly it came together.

00:29:55.000 --> 00:29:57.000
And so I would encourage you if you are working

00:29:58.000 --> 00:30:00.000
in an instance of Workbench in your organization

00:30:01.000 --> 00:30:03.000
to go ahead and try to do that same thing,

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:06.000
deploy the model that is publicly available on my GitHub

00:30:07.000 --> 00:30:09.000
and see what happens.

